2. Simple hypothesis test

\(H_0 : \alpha_5 = 0\)
\(H_1 : \alpha_5\neq 0\), \(\alpha=0.05\).

lm_reduced <- lm(df$St ~ pca$x[,1] + pca$x[,2] + pca$x[,3] + pca$x[,4])
anova(lm_reduced, lm_pca_full)

4. Reduced model’s regression line

eigen_matrix <- pca$rotation
eigen_matrix[, 2:4] <- -eigen_matrix[, 2:4]
eigen_matrix
##             PC1         PC2         PC3         PC4          PC5
## At   -0.5324451 -0.02378983  0.66774028  0.07441699  0.514316280
## Pt    0.2324522  0.82494494 -0.15779276 -0.03710662  0.489036183
## Et    0.3890860 -0.02207954  0.21720985  0.89490232 -0.009709995
## At.1 -0.3952282 -0.25963783 -0.69191108  0.33801805  0.428235605
## Pt.1  0.5957138 -0.50099959  0.05747436 -0.27924692  0.559323125
co_1 <- c(); co_2 <- c(); co_3 <- c(); co_4 <- c()
for (i in 1:5){
  co_1 <- c(co_1, eigen_matrix[i,1])
  co_2 <- c(co_2, eigen_matrix[i,2])
  co_3 <- c(co_3, eigen_matrix[i,3])
  co_4 <- c(co_4, eigen_matrix[i,4])
}

1 - (6)

1. Source of multicollinearity

In 1-(5), hypothesis test.
\(H_0 : \alpha_5 = 0\)
\(H_1 : \alpha_5\neq 0\), \(\alpha=0.05\).
We can’t reject \(H_0 : \alpha_5 = 0\).

\(H_0 : \alpha_4= \alpha_5=0\)
\(H_1 :\) not \(H_0\), \(\alpha=0.05\).
Reject \(H_0 : \alpha_4= \alpha_5=0\).
And in 1-(2), we saw relationship between (At = Pt + At.1 + Pt.1) regression model.

So we can claim 1 PC(=PC5) is the source of multicollinearity.
